Using real-time reverse transcription polymerase chain reaction (rRT-PCR) the test can be performed on respiratory samples obtained from various methods, including nasal or nasopharyngeal swab or a sample of dura or sputum sample.
Results are generally available within a few hours to 2 days.
A proposed RT-PCR test using saliva swabs or throat swabs is only reliable in the first week of illness.
Over time the virus may disappear in the lungs as it continues to multiply.
For infected people tested in the second week, an alternative sample material may be taken from the deep airway via a suction catheter or may use a fecal equipment (dura).
